{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"78"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471176"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"78"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/78"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.25,0.28,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"78"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47105"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/78"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"78"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35012"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47105"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother with a three-day history of passing maroon-coloured stool. He has been his normal active self with no abdominal pain, diarrhoea or vomiting. He has a strong appetite and has been eating well. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, and SpO2 100% on room air. There is some conjunctival pallor. His abdomen is soft with no localising signs. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 100 g/L (120-150), white blood cell count 8.0 x 10\u2079/L (4.5-13.5), and platelet count 250 x 10\u2079/L (150-400).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","Colonoscopy","Technetium-99m pertechnetate scan","Rectal suction biopsy","Contrast barium enema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGastrointestinal bleeding accounts for around 80-90 cases per 100,000 paediatric emergency department visits; however, acute haemorrhage causing clinical instability is rare in children. Whilst there are many possible causes for bleeding in children of this age, by far the commonest cause of overt, painless haemorrhage is a \u003Cstrong\u003EMeckel\u0027s diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E. Other possible causes, such as intussusception, enterocolitis and malrotation, must be considered as possible causes of gastrointestinal bleeding in children. However, in the absence of any other symptoms such as abdominal pain or a recent viral infection, an intussusception would be a very unlikely diagnosis. With this clinical picture, a bleed associated with a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum is the most likely underlying problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA Meckel\u0027s diverticulum is a true diverticulum and is often characterised by the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eectopic gastric mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E within the diverticulum. Acidic secretions can ulcerate adjacent small intestinal mucosa, leading to bleeding. A helpful memory aid is the \u0022rule of twos\u0022 - a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum is usually located 2 feet proximal to the ileocecal valve, presents before the age of two years, is seen twice as commonly in males than in females and is found in 2% of the population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the diagnosis is supported by the colour of the stool (suggesting lower gastrointestinal bleeding), as well as the absence of abdominal pain and diarrhoea. A \u003Cstrong\u003Etechnetium-99m pertechnetate scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred investigation, as it reliably identifies ectopic gastric mucosa within the diverticulum, given the preferential uptake of technetium-99m by gastric mucosal cells. Interestingly, this investigation has a sensitivity of 80-90% and specificity of 95% in children, whereas in adults, sensitivity falls to 62% and specificity to 9%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E might be done first, this is not a reliable investigation in cases of suspected Meckel\u0027s diverticulum. If it was thought that the source of the bleeding was an intussusception, then an abdominal ultrasound could be a very useful investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive diagnostic tool and would not be considered first-line.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erectal suction biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is useful when tissue diagnosis is required (e.g. Hirschsprung disease), however, is not appropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlain films do not play a significant role in the diagnosis of Meckel\u0027s diverticulum and therefore, a \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrast barium enema\u003C/strong\u003E is not the investigation of choice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ectopic gastric mucosa in a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum is the commonest cause of painless rectal bleeding in children aged one to five years."],"references":["Grady E. Gastrointestinal Bleeding Scintigraphy in the Early 21st Century. J Nucl Med. 2016 Feb;57(2):252-259","Ayse G, Ozlem T, Hayriye HG, Burcu BA, Inci NS, H\u00fclya D. Risk factors associated with clinically significant gastrointestinal bleeding in pediatric ED. Am J Emerg Med. 2018 Apr;36(4)665-668","Kotha VK, Khandelwal A, Saboo SS, Shanbhogue AK, Virmani V, Marginean EC, et al. Radiologist\u0027s perspective for the Meckel\u0027s diverticulum and its complications. Br J Radiol. 2014 May;87(1037):20130743","Aboughalia HA, Cheeney SHE, Elojeimy S, et al. Meckel diverticulum scintigraphy: technique, findings and diagnostic pitfalls Pediatric Radiology 2023; 53:493\u2013508."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"78"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-16T19:14:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T19:55:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"78"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47105"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags